    paragraph1:"The Mukden Incident, which occurred on September 18, 1931, stands as a pivotal event in early 20th-century international relations and a clear example of aggressive expansionism preceding the Second World War. The incident took place near Mukden (modern-day Shenyang) in northeastern China’s Manchuria region, a territory rich in natural resources and strategically valuable to Japan. At the time, Japan already exercised significant influence in Manchuria, particularly through control of the South Manchuria Railway. However, growing political and economic pressures within Japan led its militarists to seek full domination of the region.",
    paragraph2:"The incident itself involved the explosion of a small bomb near the railway tracks controlled by Japan. Although the damage was minimal and trains continued to operate, the Japanese military quickly blamed Chinese forces for sabotage. In reality, the explosion was orchestrated by elements of the Japanese Kwantung Army as a pretext for military invasion. Using this staged attack as justification, Japanese troops launched a full-scale occupation of Manchuria, encountering limited Chinese resistance. Within months, Japan established the puppet state of Manchukuo with the last Qing emperor, Puyi, installed as its nominal ruler, while real power remained firmly in Japanese hands.",
    paragraph3:"International reaction to the Mukden Incident was largely critical, particularly through the League of Nations, which sent the Lytton Commission to investigate. The commission concluded that Japan’s actions were aggressive and unjustified, recommending that Manchuria remain part of China. However, the League lacked effective enforcement power, and Japan simply withdrew from the organization in 1933. This failure to respond decisively exposed the League’s weakness and emboldened other aggressive powers in the years that followed. The Mukden Incident thus became a symbol of unchecked militarism and marked the beginning of Japan’s expansion across East Asia, contributing significantly to the tensions that eventually erupted into the Second World War.",
