    lng: 23.20487516252484,
    title: "Soviet Captured of Sambor",
    paragraph1:"On 29 September 1939, Soviet Red Army units captured the town of Sambor (now Sambir, Ukraine) as part of their continued advance into southeastern Poland following the collapse of organized Polish resistance. Sambor was strategically significant due to its position on key road and rail routes connecting Galicia with the Carpathian region. Its occupation further strengthened Soviet control over territories assigned to the Soviet sphere under the German–Soviet agreements.",
    paragraph2:"By late September, Polish forces in the region were largely fragmented, with many units either destroyed, captured, or attempting to withdraw toward Hungary or Romania. As a result, resistance in Sambor was limited. Soviet troops entered the town with little fighting, quickly securing administrative buildings, transport infrastructure, and communication centers. Polish officials, military officers, and members of the intelligentsia were arrested, while remaining Polish soldiers were disarmed and taken into captivity.",
    paragraph3:"The capture of Sambor completed another stage of the Red Army’s consolidation of Eastern Galicia. Alongside earlier occupations of Lwów, Tarnopol, and other regional centers, Sambor’s fall confirmed that Soviet authority had become firmly established in southeastern Poland. The town would soon be incorporated into the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic, marking the permanent loss of Polish sovereignty in the area until the end of World War II.",
    image: "/images/sambor1939.jpg",
    date: "1939-09-29",
