    lat: 60.41346,
    lng: 30.00582,
    title: "Soviet Invasion of Finland",
    paragraph1:"On November 30, 1939, the Soviet Union launched a massive invasion of Finland, beginning the conflict known as the Winter War. The attack came after Finland refused Stalin’s demands to cede territory along the Karelian Isthmus and allow Soviet bases on Finnish soil. Stalin sought to push the border away from Leningrad (now St. Petersburg) for strategic security, but Finland’s refusal was seen as defiance. Using the pretext of a staged border incident at Mainila, the Soviet Union accused Finland of aggression and declared war.",
    paragraph2:"Despite being vastly outnumbered and outgunned, the Finnish army mounted a fierce defense, utilizing its knowledge of the terrain and harsh winter conditions to resist the Red Army. The Finns employed guerrilla tactics, skiing troops, and camouflage to devastating effect, earning international admiration for their courage. Soviet forces suffered heavy casualties due to poor planning, low morale, and freezing conditions.",
    paragraph3:"After months of brutal fighting, Finland was forced to sign the Moscow Peace Treaty on March 12, 1940, ceding about 11% of its territory, including Karelia, to the Soviet Union. The conflict exposed serious weaknesses in the Red Army’s leadership and strategy, influencing later Soviet military reforms before World War II’s escalation.",
