    lat: 51.05156,
    lng: 2.38664,
    title: "Allied Forces Evacuated from Dunkirk",
    paragraph1:"The evacuation of Allied forces from Dunkirk in late May and early June 1940 stands as one of the most dramatic and heroic moments of the Second World War. Following the rapid German advance through France and Belgium, British, French, and Belgian troops found themselves surrounded near the coastal town of Dunkirk. Facing overwhelming enemy forces and cut off from supply lines, the Allied armies appeared doomed to destruction or surrender. However, the British government launched Operation Dynamo, a desperate and daring mission to rescue the encircled soldiers and preserve the core of the Allied fighting force.",
    paragraph2:"Between 26 May and 4 June 1940, a remarkable fleet of naval vessels, merchant ships, and hundreds of civilian boats—famously known as the “little ships”—crossed the English Channel to evacuate troops under constant enemy fire. Despite relentless air attacks from the German Luftwaffe and difficult conditions, approximately 338,000 soldiers were successfully rescued. While heavy equipment and supplies had to be abandoned, the survival of so many troops proved crucial to the Allied war effort.",
    paragraph3:"Often referred to as the “Miracle of Dunkirk”, the evacuation transformed a near-catastrophic defeat into a symbol of resilience, courage, and unity. It allowed Britain to continue the fight, ultimately playing a vital role in the eventual Allied victory in World War II.",
    image: "/images/dunkirk.jpg",
    date: "1940-05-26",
