    lat: 48.61199,
    lng: 39.77887,
    title: "Captain Konovalov's Heroism",
    paragraph1:"On 13 July 1942, Soviet tank commander Captain Semyon Vasilyevich Konovalov carried out one of the most remarkable individual armored actions of World War II. During the fierce summer battles on the Eastern Front, Konovalov, commanding a KV-1 heavy tank, confronted a vastly superior German armored formation near the village of Nizhnaya Mityakinskaya in the Rostov region of southern Russia. His mission unfolded at a critical moment, as German forces were advancing toward the Caucasus oil fields during Operation Blue.",
    paragraph2:"Despite overwhelming odds, Konovalov and his small crew stood their ground. Over the course of intense combat, his KV-1 tank destroyed 16 German tanks, 2 armored cars, and 2 artillery pieces, astonishing battlefield observers and severely disrupting enemy momentum. His actions demonstrated exceptional courage, tactical skill, and an unwavering commitment to defending Soviet territory. The KV-1’s strong armor and Konovalov’s expert maneuvering allowed the crew to outlast and outfight a much larger force.",
    paragraph3:"Konovalov’s stand not only inspired Soviet troops but also became a celebrated episode in Soviet wartime history. His extraordinary feat highlighted the resilience of Red Army tank crews and served as a powerful symbol of defiance against Nazi aggression during one of the most desperate stages of the war.",
