    lat: 48.75004,
    lng: 6.56666,
    title: "Bazooka Charlie's Ground Operation",
    paragraph1:"One of Major Charles “Bazooka Charlie” Carpenter’s most daring acts of heroism occurred when he left the safety of his observation aircraft and directly joined ground combat. During fierce fighting in the Lorraine Campaign of 1944, Carpenter found himself near a stalled column of U.S. Sherman tanks that had come under heavy German fire. Determined to help turn the tide, he climbed onto one of the Shermans, exposing himself to enemy fire, and took control of the tank’s mounted machine gun. With remarkable courage, he directed the tank forward toward German positions, firing continuously and rallying nearby American troops. His fearless charge inspired the men around him to counterattack, breaking the German line and reclaiming lost ground.",
    paragraph2:"This extraordinary moment revealed Carpenter’s rare blend of audacity, leadership, and devotion to his comrades. Already known for attacking tanks from the air in his rocket-equipped Piper “Rosie the Rocketer,” he now proved equally fearless on the ground. His actions cemented his reputation as one of the most unorthodox and heroic officers of World War II—willing to risk everything to protect his fellow soldiers and complete the mission.",
